%T A395863 4296,4149,3934,3751,3584,3445,26022,25245,84918,81925,78721,1068804,
%U A395863 1033480,1008379,969303,1145205,1520831,1486218,1435006,1397484,1353163,1319861
%N A395863 a(n) = fewest number of integers 1..n in a sequence, S, that gets to the maximal possible value as recorded by A395717.
%H A395863 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="https://github.com/archmageirvine/joeis/blob/master/src/irvine/oeis/a395/A395863.java">Java program</a> (github)
%e A395863 a(7)=9 because S={7,4,5,6,7,3,4,6,7} gives the sequence T={7,8,10,12,14,15,16,18,21} as described in A395717. This is the shortest sequence S that results in a sequence T with 21, the maximal possible. There are other sequences of the same length that attain this maximum of 21, but no shorter sequence can do so.
%Y A395863 A395717 is the maximal value attainable. This sequence tracks the minimal number of elements needed to get there.
